{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633656"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:57:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:57:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17491"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17491"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.09,0.81,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10181"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78584"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10181"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17491"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63926"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"6654"},{"type":"tags","id":"6655"},{"type":"tags","id":"6656"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23840"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23851"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23858"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78584"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe aortic arch gives rise to three major branches that supply blood to the upper body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the brachiocephalic trunk?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arises as the second branch of the aortic arch","Divides into left subclavian and left common carotid arteries","Divides into right subclavian and right common carotid arteries","Remains on the left side of the midline","Supplies blood to the left arm and left side of neck"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebrachiocephalic trunk divides into the right subclavian and right common carotid arteries \u003C/strong\u003E(Image). It is the first and largest branch of the aortic arch and arises posterior to the manubrium of the sternum. It courses superiorly and to the right, crossing the midline before it bifurcates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDivides into left subclavian and left common carotid arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - These vessels arise separately as the second and third branches of the aortic arch\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupplies blood to the left arm and left side of neck\u003C/strong\u003E - The brachiocephalic trunk supplies the right arm and right side of head and neck\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArises as the second branch of the aortic arch\u003C/strong\u003E - The left common carotid artery is the second branch\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemains on the left side of the midline\u003C/strong\u003E - The brachiocephalic trunk crosses the midline to reach the right side\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the branching pattern of the aortic arch is clinically important for procedures involving the great vessels and for interpreting radiological imaging of the thorax.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The brachiocephalic trunk is the first branch of the aortic arch and divides into the right subclavian and right common carotid arteries.","The brachiocephalic trunk supplies blood to the right arm, right side of the head and neck.","The brachiocephalic trunk is the only branch of the aortic arch that crosses the midline."],"references":["Popieluszko P, Henry BH, Sanna B, et al. A systematic review and meta-analysis of variations in branching patterns of the adult aortic arch. J Vasc Surg 2018;68:298-306","Moore KL, Dalley AF, Agur A. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Lippincott Williams and Wilkins; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63926"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17491"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21328"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21328"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/vz4qt86GVOHszhdy91Dzcr8YGGsUP8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/vz4qt86GVOHszhdy91Dzcr8YGGsUP8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":321,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63926"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T17:27:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T17:27:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10181"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78584"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tag